 very essence of democracy.In this provocative and lucidly argued book, Richard Tuck draws on the distinction made by the Abbé Sieyès, a leading political theorist of the French Revolution, between “active” citizens (the electorate) and “passive” ones (those who are represented by the institutions of the state). Tuck traces our current representative view of democracy to Sieyès and contrasts him with Rousseau, a theorist of active self-rule by the people. Tuck argues that modern theories of democracy have effectively turned us into passive citizens and calls for a renewal of a majoritarian democracy that realizes the full potential of active citizenship.Based on the prestigious Tanner Lectures delivered at Princeton University’s Center for Human Values, Active and Passive Citizens is edited and introduced by Stephen Macedo and includes commentary by political theorists Simone Chambers, Joshua Cohen, John Ferejohn, and Melissa Schwartzberg.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aPolitical participation. 0aPolitical sciencexPhilosophy. 0aRepresentative government and representation. 0aVoting. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh  aAmerican political science association.  aCenter for Human Values.  aFree Riding.  aHobbes.  aJohn Ferejohn.  aJoshua Cohen.  aKarl Marx.  aMelissa Schwarzberg.  aNatural Rights Theories.  aPhilosophy and Government.  aPrinceton University.  aRousseau.  aRousseau’s misogyny.  aSenate.  aSieyes.  aSimone Chambers.  aStephen Macedo.  aTanner Lectures.  aThe Rights of War and Peace.  aThe Sleeping Sovereign.  aTuck’s Democracy.  aVoting.  aactive citizenship.  aactive democracy.  aassociation for political theory.  aauthorization.  acitizen.  acitizenship.  acivil rights.  aconstitution.  ademocracy.  adem